  "prompt": "Will people still be able to have websites with no net neutrality?",
  "response": "Yes, people will still be able to have websites even in a situation where net neutrality is not enforced. However, the implications of the absence of net neutrality could affect how websites are accessed and experienced by users.\n\nWithout net neutrality, Internet Service Providers (ISPs) could potentially prioritize certain types of traffic over others, creating a tiered internet experience. This could mean:\n\n1. **Prioritization of Content**: ISPs might prioritize their own services or those of companies that pay for better access, which could lead to slower speeds for competing websites that do not pay for such prioritization.\n\n2. **Increased Costs for Businesses**: Smaller businesses or new startups may struggle to compete if they cannot afford to pay ISPs for prioritized access, potentially limiting their visibility and reach.\n\n3. **Variability in Access**: Users might experience inconsistent access to websites depending on their ISP, as some sites may load faster or perform better than others based on the ISP's practices.\n\nWhile websites will still exist, the ease of access and competitive landscape may be affected, which could have broader implications for innovation, entrepreneurship, and freedom of information online.",
